Construction (b) above is natural in (G,X,F). We set
2382hodge-theory-iii-6.1.2.3hodge-theory-iii-6.1.2.3.xmlEquation6.1.2.3hodge-theory-iii-6.1.2 \operatorname {H}^\bullet (X,G;F) = \operatorname {H}^\bullet ([X/G]_\bullet ,F^\bullet ) \tag{6.1.2.3}
(mixed cohomology of X,G with coefficients in F). Under the hypotheses of (a), if F is the inverse image of F^{-1} on S=X/G, then
2383hodge-theory-iii-6.1.2.4hodge-theory-iii-6.1.2.4.xmlEquation6.1.2.4hodge-theory-iii-6.1.2 \operatorname {H}^\bullet (X,G;F) = \operatorname {H}^\bullet (X/G,F^{-1}) \tag{6.1.2.4}
(for a principal homogeneous space). This generalises (which is the case F=\underline {\mathbb {Z}}).

fr:mainmatter.fr:p:
Let P be a principal homogeneous space for the group G on S.
    The evident morphism
           \operatorname {cosq}(P\to  S)       = [P/G]_\bullet        \to  [P^t/G]_\bullet        = B_{\bullet  G}     
    defines a composite morphism

    2415hodge-theory-iii-6.1.3.1hodge-theory-iii-6.1.3.1.xmlEquation6.1.3.1hodge-theory-iii-6.1.3         [P]         \colon  \operatorname {H}^\bullet (B_{\bullet  G})         \to  \operatorname {H}^\bullet ([P/G]_\bullet )         \xleftarrow [(6.1.2.2)]{\sim } \operatorname {H}^\bullet (S).       \tag{6.1.3.1}

Let G be a Lie group, B_G a classifying space for G, and a\colon  U_G\to  B_G the universal principal homogeneous G-space.
    Let X be a G-space;
    then X\times  U_G is a principal homogeneous G-space over X\times  U_G/G such that, for every equivariant sheaf F on X, \operatorname {pr}_1^*F is the inverse image of a sheaf F^G on X\times  U_G/G.
    Since U_G is contractible, and by , we have

    2417hodge-theory-iii-6.1.4.1hodge-theory-iii-6.1.4.1.xmlEquation6.1.4.1hodge-theory-iii-6.1.4         \operatorname {H}^\bullet (X,G;F)         \xrightarrow {\sim } \operatorname {H}^\bullet (X\times  U_G,G;\operatorname {pr}_1^*F)         \xleftarrow {\sim } \operatorname {H}^\bullet (X\times  U_G/G,F^G).       \tag{6.1.4.1}

html:ol.html:li:
If T is a torus with character group X(T), then
339hodge-theory-iii-6.1.6.2hodge-theory-iii-6.1.6.2.xmlEquation6.1.6.2hodge-theory-iii-6.1.6 \operatorname {H}^\bullet (T,\mathbb {Z}) \simeq \bigwedge ^\bullet X(T) \tag{6.1.6.2}
(an isomorphism of graded Hopf algebras).

fr:mainmatter.fr:p:
Let G be a connected linear algebraic group. Let P^\bullet \subset \operatorname {H}^\bullet (G,\mathbb {Q}) be the primitive part of the Hopf algebra \operatorname {H}^\bullet (G,\mathbb {Q}). It is a mixed Hodge substructure. We have that P^{2i}(G)=0, and P^{2i-1}(G) is pure of type (i,i). Finally, the isomorphism
2460hodge-theory-iii-9.1.5.1hodge-theory-iii-9.1.5.1.xmlEquation9.1.5.1hodge-theory-iii-9.1.5 \bigwedge P^\bullet (G) \to \operatorname {H}^\bullet (G,\mathbb {Q}) \tag{9.1.5.1}
is an isomorphism of mixed Hodge structures.

Let G be a connected linear algebraic group. Let P^\bullet \subset \operatorname {H}^\bullet (G,\mathbb {Q}) be the primitive part of the Hopf algebra \operatorname {H}^\bullet (G,\mathbb {Q}). It is a mixed Hodge substructure. We have that P^{2i}(G)=0, and P^{2i-1}(G) is pure of type (i,i). Finally, the isomorphism
2460hodge-theory-iii-9.1.5.1hodge-theory-iii-9.1.5.1.xmlEquation9.1.5.1hodge-theory-iii-9.1.5 \bigwedge P^\bullet (G) \to \operatorname {H}^\bullet (G,\mathbb {Q}) \tag{9.1.5.1}
is an isomorphism of mixed Hodge structures.

Let X be a smooth and proper algebraic space on which a connected linear algebraic group G acts via \rho \colon  G\times  X\to  X.
    Then the diagram


    \usepackage {amsmath}
    \usepackage {amssymb}
    \usepackage {tikz-cd}
  \begin {tikzcd}
      \operatorname {H}^\bullet (X,\mathbb {Q})
        \ar [r,"\rho ^*"]
        \ar [d,equals]
      & \operatorname {H}^\bullet (X,\mathbb {Q})\otimes \operatorname {H}^\bullet (G,\mathbb {Q})
    \\\operatorname {H}^\bullet (X,\mathbb {Q})\otimes _\mathbb {Q}\mathbb {Q}
        \ar [r,equals]
      & \operatorname {H}^\bullet (X,\mathbb {Q})\otimes \operatorname {H}^0(G,\mathbb {Q})
        \ar [u]
    \end {tikzcd}

    commutes.

It suffices to prove that, for i>0, the Künneth components
               \begin {gathered}           \operatorname {H}^n(\overline {X},\mathbb {Q})           \to  \operatorname {H}^n(X,\mathbb {Q})           \to  \operatorname {H}^{n-i}(X,\mathbb {Q})\otimes \operatorname {H}^i(G,\mathbb {Q})         \\(\text {resp.}\quad            \operatorname {H}^n(X,\mathbb {Q})           \to  \operatorname {H}^{n-i}(X,\mathbb {Q})\otimes \operatorname {H}^i(G,\mathbb {Q})           \to  \operatorname {H}^{n-i}(\widetilde {X},\mathbb {Q})\otimes \operatorname {H}^i(G,\mathbb {Q})           )         \end {gathered}       
      are zero.
      In case (i) (resp. case (ii)), we have ()
               \begin {gathered}           W_n\operatorname {H}^n(\overline {X},\mathbb {Q})           = \operatorname {H}^n(\overline {X},\mathbb {Q})         \\(\text {resp.}\quad            W_n\operatorname {H}^n(X,\mathbb {Q})           = \operatorname {H}^n(X,\mathbb {Q})           )         \end {gathered}       
      and so, by  and ,
               \begin {gathered}           W_n(\operatorname {H}^{n-i}(X,\mathbb {Q})\otimes \operatorname {H}^i(G,\mathbb {Q}))           = 0         \\(\text {resp.}\quad            W_n(\operatorname {H}^{n-i}(\widetilde {X},\mathbb {Q})\otimes \operatorname {H}^i(G,\mathbb {Q}))           = 0           )         \end {gathered}       
      whence the claim.
